  "prompt": "How was the International Space Station built?",
  "response": "The International Space Station (ISS) was built through a collaborative effort of multiple countries, primarily the United States, Russia, Canada, Japan, and several European countries. Here's a brief overview of its construction:\n\n1. Assembly began in 1998 with the launch of the first module, the Russian Zarya module.\n\n2. The construction was a complex, multi-year process involving numerous space shuttle missions and Russian rocket launches.\n\n3. Modules were launched separately and then connected in space:\n- Each module was pre-fabricated on Earth\n- Astronauts used robotic arms to attach modules together\n- Modular design allowed for gradual assembly in orbit\n\n4. Major components were launched and assembled piece by piece:\n- Russian modules\n- US modules\n- European modules\n- Japanese modules\n- Canadian robotic arms and components\n\n5. Construction continued from 1998 to 2011, with the final major US module installed in 2011.\n\n6. The process involved over 30 missions to transport and assemble modules, solar panels, and other critical infrastructure.\n\n7. Astronauts conducted numerous spacewalks to connect modules, install equipment, and perform maintenance during construction.\n\nThe ISS represents an unprecedented international engineering and collaborative achievement in space exploration.",
